photo.description: This plaque, installed at the visitor entrance of Neuschwanstein, commemorates the 150th anniversary of the founding of the "Union of Craftsmen for Construction of the Royal Castle of Hohenschwangau" by King Ludwig, which is known today as the "Private Health Care Association" in Schwangau. This revolutionary association provided 65% of a sick or injured worker's wages , 10.40 Marks on average, for up to 15 weeks, and was funded by a large grant from the King, and employee contributions of 70 pfennigs a week.

photo.description: This is the village of Schwangau, as seen from the Neuschwanstein Palace. It is located in a valley called Königswinkel, or the king's nook. Steeply rising mountains, beautiful lakes and romantic castles are the most famous landmarks. Lake Forggensee is an artificial lake that makes up 16 square kilometers. It is named after the part of Schwangau (Forggen) that had to be flooded to form the lake and a paradise musical theater.

photo.description: This is a view of the town of Hohenschwangau from the Neuschwanstein palace. Construction on King Ludwig II's castle began in 1869 and overlooks the lower Hohenschwangau Castle which belonged to Crown Prince Maximilian II of Bavaria, Ludwig II's father. Also in the picture in the Alpsee, a lake favored by Ludwig II because of the wild swan inhabitants. Hohenschwangau is in the district of Ostallgäu in Bavaria, Germany - a small tourist destination only accessible by bus or passenger vehicle. The nearest train station is 4 km away in the larger town of Füssen.

photo.description: Here is another shot of Neuschwanstein. It shows the inner courtyard of the castle. The castle was intended as a personal refuge for the reclusive king, but it was opened to the paying public immediately after his death in 1886. Since then over 60 million people have visited Neuschwanstein Castle. More than 1.3 million people visit annually, with up to 6,000 per day in the summer. The palace has appeared prominently in several movies and was the inspiration for Disneyland's Sleeping Beauty Castle and later, similar structures. photo.description: This adornment above a door inside the entrance archway reads "At Day or Night - The Faithful Guard", Had Neuschwanstein been a functioning castle with a defensive purpose, the room behind the door would have held the castle hounds. It was common in Germany to guard castles and estates with Hovawarts.
photo.title: Guarding the Gatehaus

photo.description: The horseshoe over this door symbolizes the stablemeister's chambers at Neuschwanstein. Usually the horses were kept in the town of Hohenschwangau, near the castle with the same name. This room would be a living chamber for the Stablemeister when he was at Neuschwanstein. This horseshoe is not a symbol of luck, as it is upside down, allowing the luck it holds to run out.
